+   git clone https://github.com/VIVIANAPLATA16/clearpath-health.git
+   cd clearpath-health
+   ```
+
+2. **Install dependencies:**
+   ```bash
+   npm install
+   ```
+
+3. **Run the development server:**
+   ```bash
+   npm run dev
+   ```
+   The app will be available at `http://localhost:3000`.
+
+> No environment variables are required to run the demo — the orchestration layer responds through the local Fail-Safe queue described below, so judges can clone and evaluate it immediately with zero configuration.
+
+---
+
+## 🗺️ Application Map
+
+| Route | Description |
+|---|---|
+| `/` | Landing page — value proposition, impact stats, and how-it-works overview. |
+| `/nueva` | **Core demo flow.** Clinic staff submits a new authorization request (patient, diagnosis/CIE-10, procedure, doctor, EPS). The 4-agent pipeline animates in real time while the request is scored. |
+| `/dashboard` | Medical Auditor Dashboard — live table of authorization cases, filterable by status (`AUTO-APROBADO` / `REVISIÓN HUMANA`) and searchable by patient, service, EPS, or case ID. |
+| `/caso/[id]` | Full case detail: pertinence score, AI reasoning, coverage checklist, risk factors, and agent timeline. |
+| `/agentes` | Orchestration panel — real-time status of the 4 AI agents and their daily throughput. |
+| `POST /api/process` | The core authorization engine. Receives the request payload and returns a clinical pertinence score (0–100), an `AUTO_APROBADO` / `REVISION_HUMANA` decision, and a structured AI-generated justification. |
+
+---
+
+## 🛡️ Fail-Safe Mode (Resilience by Design)
+
+During development, the team hit authentication blocks (`invalid_client` / `access_denied`) while wiring the live connection to the UiPath Cloud Identity Server for this staging tenant — a common friction point when integrating a hackathon prototype with a freshly provisioned enterprise Orchestrator org on a tight deadline.
+
+Instead of stalling, the backend was designed to **degrade gracefully**: every request is processed and scored locally first, then queued for orchestration sync. If the live UiPath connection is temporarily unavailable, the request is **never lost** — it's held safely in a local queue, ready to sync the moment connectivity is restored. This reflects a production-grade principle the architecture honors from day one: *a patient's authorization request should never depend on the uptime of a single external API.*
+
+In the running app, this is surfaced transparently to the user as a **`Modo Respaldo Local activo · UiPath Sandbox`** badge wherever a request is processed.
+
+---
